<!-- OPENING -->
<section class="opening reveal">
  <div>
    <p class="opening-eyebrow">Why we walk</p>
    <h2>Nature doesn't need<br>to be explained<br>to be <em>medicine</em></h2>
  </div>
  <div>
    <p>The Japanese call it shinrin-yoku. Forest bathing. The measurable, documented physiological effect of spending time surrounded by trees — cortisol drops, blood pressure lowers, immune markers improve, mood lifts. The science is real. The experience is older than the science by several thousand years.</p>
    <p>These walks are not nature appreciation classes. They are a guided experience of the plant world in its season, led by someone whose whole practice is rooted in botanical medicine — who can show you why the plants that grow in damp ground in February are precisely the plants the body needs after winter, or why the nervines that flower in midsummer are nature's answer to the pace that summer demands of us.</p>
    <p><em>Slow, attentive, deliberately paced.</em> We stop often. We smell things, touch things, taste things (safely). We talk. We are quiet. We leave different from how we arrived — and that is not an accident.</p>
  </div>
</section>

